# 🌐 Part 1 — How JavaScript Runs in Browser

When you open a website, this happens internally:

1. Browser loads HTML
2. Browser loads CSS
3. Browser finds <script>
4. JS Engine executes JS
5. Page becomes interactive

## 🔎 Inside the Browser — Real Execution Flow

Browser has:

* Rendering Engine → shows page
* JavaScript Engine → runs JS
* Web APIs → timers, DOM, events

Example code:
html
<button id="btn">Click</button>

<script>
document.getElementById("btn").onclick = function() {
  alert("Hello");
}
</script>

Execution:
Browser reads HTML
↓
Creates DOM tree
↓
Finds <script>
↓
JS engine runs code
↓
Event listener attached
↓
User clicks
↓
Function runs
↓
Alert shown

# ⚙️ JavaScript Engine Internals (Important)

JS engine runs code in 2 phases:

## 1️⃣ Parsing

Engine reads code → checks syntax
Example:
let x = 5;
Converted to internal structure.

## 2️⃣ Compilation + Execution
Modern engines (V8) convert JS → machine code → execute.

So:
JS → Bytecode → Machine code → CPU runs

---

# 🧵 Execution Context (How JS Tracks Code)

When JS runs, engine creates:

👉 Execution Context = environment to run code

Contains:

* Variables
* Functions
* Scope
* this value

Example:
javascript code

let a = 10;
function test() {
  let b = 20;
}

Execution order:

Global Context created
↓
a stored
↓
test stored
↓
test() called
↓
Function context created
↓
b stored
↓
Function ends

---

# 🧭 Call Stack (How Functions Run)

JavaScript uses stack:
Last In → First Out
Example:
javascript code:
function one() {
  two();
}
function two() {
  console.log("Hello");
}

one();

Stack flow:

Global
↓
one()
↓
two()
↓
console.log
↓
two ends
↓
one ends
---

# ⏱️ Event Loop (Why JS Handles Clicks & Timers)

JavaScript is **single-threaded** (one task at time).

But it handles:

* Clicks
* Timers
* Network
* Animations

Using:

👉 Event Loop
👉 Callback Queue
👉 Web APIs

Example:

javascript code
setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("Hi");
}, 2000);

console.log("Start");

Output:
Start
Hi (after 2 sec)

Why?
setTimeout → Web API
↓
Timer finished → Queue
↓
Stack empty → Event loop pushes
↓
Callback runs


# 🖥️ Part 2 — How JavaScript Runs in Backend (Node.js)

Now the main question you asked 👍

JavaScript normally runs in browser.
But backend needs:

* File system
* Database
* Network
* Server

Browsers don’t allow this.

So Node.js was created.

---

# 🧩 What is Node.js?

Node.js = JavaScript runtime outside browser

It includes:

* V8 engine (same as Chrome)
* OS access
* File system
* Networking
* HTTP server

So JS can run on computer/server.

---

# ⚙️ How Node.js Runs JavaScript

When you run:

node app.js

This happens:

1. Node starts
2. Loads V8 engine
3. Reads app.js
4. Parses JS
5. Compiles
6. Executes

Exactly like browser — but without DOM.

# 🔎 Example Backend Program

app.js:

```javascript
console.log("Server started");
```

Run:
node app.js
```

Output:

Server started

JS ran outside browser ✅

# 🌐 Backend Server Example (Important)

```javascript
const http = require("http");

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  res.write("Hello from server");
  res.end();
});

server.listen(3000);
```

Execution flow:

node app.js
↓
Node loads http module
↓
Creates server
↓
Listens on port 3000
↓
Browser requests localhost:3000
↓
Callback runs
↓
Response sent
```

---

# 📦 Node.js Architecture (Important)

Node has:

* V8 engine
* Event loop
* Libuv (async I/O)
* OS bindings

So Node handles many users efficiently.

---

# 🧵 Backend Event Loop

Same concept as browser.

Example:

```javascript
const fs = require("fs");

fs.readFile("data.txt", () => {
  console.log("File read");
});

console.log("Start");
```

Output:

```
Start
File read
```

Why?

```
readFile → OS
↓
Node continues
↓
Callback queued
↓
Event loop runs
```

---

# 🔥 How Backend JS Handles Requests

Server flow:

```
Client request
↓
Node receives
↓
Event loop assigns callback
↓
Handler runs
↓
Response sent
```

One thread can handle thousands users.

---

# ⚖️ Browser JS vs Node JS

Difference:

Browser:

* Has DOM
* Has window
* UI events

Node:

* No DOM
* Has file system
* Has server APIs

Example:

Browser only:

```javascript
document.getElementById()
```

Node only:

```javascript
require("fs")
```

